==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*walo-'', from Indo-European ''*welə-'' ‘wound, injure’.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''wal-'' (in [[waldad|waldâd]] ‘murderous deed’), Old High German [[wal]], Old Norse [[valr]] (in [[Valkyrie]], lit. ‘chooser of the slain’).  The Indo-European root is also the source of Latin [[vulnus]] ‘wound’, Old Irish [[fuil]] ‘blood’.

